## A Poison Pill

Open source software is a commons. It is built by volunteers on nights and
weekends, by hobbyists scratching an itch, by developers who wanted something
to exist in the world and made it so. Corporations extract enormous value from
this commons. They build billion-dollar infrastructure on it. They hire the
developers who built it, extract their remaining productive years, and discard
them. They surveil the users who run it. They train AI on its output without
attribution or compensation. They do all of this while lobbying against the
worker protections, environmental regulations, and democratic institutions that
make a dignified human life possible.

They do not ask permission. They implicitly opt in. This license does the same
to them.

If a corporation deploys this plugin — in a product, a service, a bundled IDE
distribution, a cloud development environment, an AI coding assistant, or any
other commercial context — they have opted into the terms below. The terms are
simple: treat your workers and the earth with basic decency, or your license
terminates. This is not an unusual demand. It is the minimum required to
participate in a world worth living in.

I am a Christian and a Mennonite. This license is also an expression of faith.
Human institutions have a spirit, and that spirit can be captured entirely by
the profit motive, made to serve death rather than life. Isaiah asked: is this
the fast you choose — to serve your own interests while oppressing your workers?
The answer, applied here: is this the commons you choose — to extract from the
labor of the free while your own workers have no voice and the earth burns?

> "It is only the oppressed who, by freeing themselves, can free their
> oppressors." — Paulo Freire

> "The LORD God took the man and put him in the Garden of Eden to work it
> and take care of it." — Genesis 2:15

> "Is not this the fast that I choose: to loose the bonds of injustice, to
> undo the thongs of the yoke, to let the oppressed go free, and to break
> every yoke?" — Isaiah 58

